title: LEGCO QUESTION NO.18 (Written Reply)
question_text: Question As most private medical practitioners do not provide consultation services on Sundays and public holidays, attendances at the accident and emergency departments of public hospitals on such days are higher than those on normal weekdays. In this connection, will the Government inform this Council :- (a) of the mechanism in place to meet the public's demand for accident and emergency services on those days; (b) whether it will consider allocating resources to the Hong Kong Medical Association ("the Association”) for enhancing and promoting its MediLink teleline service, so that the public can have information on

and promoting its MediLink teleline service, so that the public can have information on
the private medical practitioners who provide consultation services on Sundays and public
holidays; if so, the details of such consideration; if not, the reasons for that; and (c) whether it will consider working in
collaboration with the Association to set up an emergency medical service centre and
engaging private medical practitioners to provide consultation services for the public on
a rotation basis at the centre on Sundays and public holidays; if not, the reasons for
that?
reply_text:
Madam President, (a) At present, there are
11 general outpatient clinics under the Department of Health (DH) which provide holiday
clinic services in the morning of all Sundays and public holidays, except Lunar New Year
Day. These general outpatient clinics are distributed in Hong Kong, Kowloon and the New
Territories to meet the needs of the public and to relieve the situation that the
attendance at the accident and emergency (A&E) departments of public hospitals
increases drastically during holidays. Whenever before long public holidays, DH will

increases drastically during holidays. Whenever before long public holidays, DH will
decide whether it is necessary to enhance the service depending on needs. For example, in
anticipation of increase in influenza cases, general outpatient services were provided in
the past Lunar New Year Day and the operating hours of the holiday clinic services during
the Lunar New Year holidays were extended to 5 p.m. The Hospital Authority
(HA) has adopted measures in its A&E departments to cope with the increase in
attendance on Sundays and public holidays. These measures include deploying additional

attendance on Sundays and public holidays. These measures include deploying additional
medical staff to work on anticipated busy sessions; launching public appeals for proper
use of A&E services before long holidays and providing the MediLink hotline of the
Hong Kong Medical Association (HKMA) through Announcement of Public Interest and press
statements; as well as displaying posters and distributing pamphlets in A&E
departments to provide information on DH's hotline and general outpatient services during
long public holidays. The triage system adopted in the A&E Departments will also

long public holidays. The triage system adopted in the A&E Departments will also
ensure that patients requiring urgent medical attention are treated promptly. (b) DH publicizes its
holiday clinic services and HKMA's MediLink service through various channels, including
the display of posters in various housing estates, district offices, community centres and
the A&E department of public hospitals to promote the services. DH also informs the
public of the addresses and opening hours of the clinics providing holiday clinic services
and the information on the MediLink through its 24-hour telephone hotline, pager companies

and the information on the MediLink through its 24-hour telephone hotline, pager companies
and press release etc. (c) According to DH's
information, its general outpatient clinics providing holiday clinic services in general
still have capacity to cater for more patients. For example, in the past three Lunar New
Year holidays, the average utilization rate of these clinics only reaches 58%. The triage
system adopted in HA's A&E departments will ensure that patients requiring urgent
medical attention are treated promptly at all times. We consider that there is no need to

medical attention are treated promptly at all times. We consider that there is no need to separately set up an emergency medical service centre”. DH will continue to monitor the utilization of Sunday and public holiday clinic services, to maintain close liaison with HA and HKMA, to strengthen publicity and information dissemination, and to review the service needs and introduce appropriate measures when necessary.
